defaultThe ENA/Delta-ee report methodology developed a residential heat model that combines the following in order to assess the 
defaultoptimal appliance technology pathways, by property type, based on known/emerging heating technology, required to meet carbon and renew
defaultable targets, highlighting the impact on consumers (cost to change and behavioural) and the potential load changes on the gas and electricity distribution networks out to 2050
default&#xa0;defaultThe report contains:default&#xa0;defaultA housing stock modeldefault dividing the UK housing stock into 
default35 segments according to fuel availability and use, age, and building type. For each segment the thermal demand and how this changes decade by decade to 2050 is defined. 
default&#xa0;defaultA technology performance modeldefault: which forecasts future cost and performance– coverin
defaultg: gas boiler; gas heat pump; low electrical efficiency micro-CHP; high electrical efficiency micro-CHP; gas boiler + solar thermal; air source heat pump; ground source heat pump; hybrid gas boiler + air source heat pump; biomass boiler; district heating; 
defaultdirect electric (storage) heating. 
default&#xa0;defaultA customer choice modeldefault that incorporates the physical fit of different technologies with different parts of the housing stock; customer uptake based on payback and upfront cost; and customer attitudes to different technologies. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis in turn led to the development of three 
defaultbasic scenarios: Customer Choice; Electrification and Heat Networks; and Balanced Transition.
default&#xa0;
